{"title_page": "Dolls (1987 film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dolls\n| image          = Dollsposter1987.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Stuart Gordon]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Charles Band]]\n* [[Brian Yuzna]]\n}}\n| writer         = [[Ed Naha]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Stephen Lee (actor)|Stephen Lee]]\n* [[Guy Rolfe]]\n* [[Hilary Mason]]\n* Ian Patrick Williams\n* Carolyn Purdy Gordon\n* Cassie Stuart\n* [[Bunty Bailey]]\n* Carrie Lorraine\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* Fuzzbee Morse\n* Victor Spiegel\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Mac Ahlberg]]\n| editing        = [[Lee Percy]]\n| distributor    = [[Empire Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1987|4|27|[[Seattle International Film Festival|Seattle Film Festival]]|ref1=<ref name=afi/>|1987|5|22|Los Angeles|ref2=<ref name=afi/>|1987|11|6|New York City|ref3=<ref>{{cite news|work=[[New York Daily News]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41127985/daily_news/|title='Running Man' a Running Joke, But Fun|date=November 18, 1987|via=Newspapers.com|location=New York City, New York}}</ref>}}\n| runtime        = 77 minutes<ref name=afi/>\n| country        = United States<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Film/57605-DOLLS?sid=510a192f-a295-44fc-a9f9-5b7f467d2451&sr=14.645739&cp=1&pos=0|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|location=Los Angeles, California|title=Dolls|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227021918/https://catalog.afi.com/Film/57605-DOLLS?sid=510a192f-a295-44fc-a9f9-5b7f467d2451&sr=14.645739&cp=1&pos=0|archive-date=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $2 million\n| gross          = $3.5 million\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n\n'''''Dolls''''' is a 1987 American [[horror film]] directed by [[Stuart Gordon]], written by [[Ed Naha]], and starring [[Stephen Lee (actor)|Stephen Lee]], [[Guy Rolfe]], [[Hilary Mason]], Ian Patrick Williams, and [[Bunty Bailey]]. Its plot follows six people who seek shelter during a storm in the mansion of an elderly puppetmaker and his wife, only to find that the various puppets and dolls in the home contain the imprisoned spirits of criminals. It was produced by [[Charles Band]] and [[Brian Yuzna]], through Band's [[Empire Pictures]].\n\nThe film was a commercial failure, grossing $3.5 million worldwide against a budget of only $2 million.{{Citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n==Plot==\nA violent [[thunderstorm]] strands a couple and child in the [[gothic fiction|gothic]] English countryside: little Judy, who is traveling with her selfish, uncaring father, David and her rich, callous, arrogant stepmother Rosemary. David only has Judy due to a court order and barely tolerates the little girl's presence, while Rosemary openly dislikes her stepdaughter. After their car is stuck in the mud and the rain begins, they find a mansion. After breaking in, they are found by the owners, a kindly older couple called Gabriel and Hilary Hartwicke. Rosemary threw Judy's beloved [[teddy bear]] into the bushes while out in the rain, so Gabriel gifts her a new [[doll]], Mr. Punch. They are invited to stay and while eating, Isabel and Enid (two British punk rocker hitchhikers) barge in with the person who picked them up, the naive yet good-natured Ralph. Gabriel reveals himself to be a talented toy maker; their house is filled with dolls, puppets, and many other beautifully detailed and handmade toys like Mr. Punch. The Hartwickes invite the stranded travelers to join them to stay as guests until the storm ends and show them to their rooms.\n\nAs it turns out, Isabel has thievery on her mind, and before taking Ralph's wallet and car, she plans on stealing any valuables and antiques the Hartwickes own. Enid just wants to get through the night. Isabel sneaks out and, while casing a room, is brutally attacked by the dolls, who spring to life and beat her before throwing her into the hallway in front of Judy. Unable to speak or even cry for help due to her extensive injuries, she extends her hand in pleading; but before Judy can react in any way, Isabel is dragged off to the attic before her eyes. Judy runs to tell her father and Rosemary, but they accuse her of making up stories and send her away. Judy then goes to Ralph's room to tell him what happened and since she woke him up, he thinks she's dreaming. However, as she turns to leave, he notices blood on her slippers, so he agrees to accompany her. However, on the way downstairs, some of the dolls delay them by tripping Ralph, and he falls down the stairs. He's fine when he gets up, except for a seeming bite mark that he believes came from a rat. They arrive at David and Rosemary's room, and Judy tries to tell him what happened; but they, along with Enid, simply ignore Judy and accuse Ralph of both attacking Isabel and being a pedophile. Upset at the treatment of both her and her new friend, Judy runs off with her father behind her. While looking for Judy, Ralph runs into Gabriel, who tells him that it's not blood but paint that he and Judy stepped in; and Isabel probably just got lost in one of the halls in the large house. Satisfied, he continues his search for Judy, finding her in the kitchen along with Mr. Punch. She continues to try to convince him, but he doesn't believe in the dolls until Mr. Punch himself actually speaks up which shocks both of them. \n\nRosemary is later ambushed and attacked repeatedly by the toys before accidentally leaping to her death (thinking she was jumping over them) out of a window. Enid goes looking for Isabel and finds her almost entirely transformed into a doll version of herself, but still able to attempt to warn her friend to \"go back\". Enid is then attacked by a horde of toys and eventually shot to death by toy soldiers. Rosemary's body has been taken to her bedroom, where, covered in a sheet, her death is not yet noticed by David. A locked room opens itself to Judy and Ralph. Ralph asks if they are Judy's 'little people' whom she spoke of and she informs him that they are. Encountering the dolls gathered together, Ralph ends up getting caught up in a trap the toys set for the other adults and is nearly hurt badly, until Judy convinces them to save him since he is her friend and on their side, too. Afterwards, they are stuck until the dolls decide what to do with them. David, fresh out of the shower, tries to talk to his wife, but finally finds her dead. Believing Ralph murdered her, David prepares to kill him. Now safe from the toys, Judy and Ralph run into the workshop where an angry David finds them. Ralph attempts to tell him what is going on, but David has taken leave of his reason. Ralph has learned the truth about the dolls and refuses to use them to fight, but David doesn't believe and knocks both his daughter and Ralph unconscious when they resist before David is assaulted by Mr. Punch. During their fight, the other dolls drag the unconscious Ralph and Judy away to safety. Mr. Punch is destroyed by David with a mallet after a fierce struggle.\n\nDavid is then confronted by Gabriel and Hilary. It is revealed that Gabriel and Hilary are actually a [[Wizard (paranormal)|wizard]] and [[witch]] couple who see toys as the heart and soul of childhood and believe toys will be around for as long as children (or even those with the hearts of children) want them. They also believe that the bitterness adults feel can turn to love if they surrender to the goodwill that toys provide. They explain that people come to their house every now and then and spend the night. When this happens, they test their visitors to see if they can change or were good from the start, giving them a sporting chance to save themselves. Some people, like Ralph (people who are able to see the love and respect of childhood) and children (like Judy), are saved/spared and leave the house with a much better perspective of life. However, those like David, Rosemary, Isabel, and Enid who refuse to change their ways can never leave, since they must play a new role in the world of children. It is shown that that new role is to become a child's toy when David is (apparently painfully) transformed into a doll to replace Mr. Punch when he attempts to attack the couple.\n\nThe next morning, Ralph and Judy wake up and are convinced by Gabriel and Hilary that the night's events were all just a dream, and receive a letter saying that David is leaving Judy behind because he never was a good father to her and that she will be much happier living in [[Boston]] with her mother. The letter also states that her father and stepmother are moving to another country and changing their names, and have also taken both Enid and Isabel with them, but have left enough money behind for Judy and Ralph to buy plane tickets back to Boston. Ralph and Judy then leave the house together after being bid farewell by Gabriel and Hilary, who invite them to come back whenever they want. As they get into Ralph's car, Judy is overjoyed to find her lost teddy sitting in the front seat, but then decides he would be happier living with the dolls and gives him to the Hartwickes as a gift. As they drive off to the airport, Judy, who has grown quite fond of Ralph, tells him that he will really like her mother and hints to him that if he would like to stay with her and her mother, he could be Judy's new father. Though Ralph does not answer, he expresses interest in the idea.\n\nThe film ends with Mr. and Mrs. Bowers and the punk girls sitting on a shelf as dolls. Just then, another car with [[Dysfunctional family|another family with a set of obnoxious parents]] suddenly arrives, and their car gets stuck in a mud hole yards from the mansion.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast list|\n* Ian Patrick Williams as David Bower\n* Carolyn Purdy Gordon as Rosemary Bower\n* Carrie Lorraine as Judy Bower\n* [[Guy Rolfe]] as Gabriel Hartwicke\n* [[Hilary Mason]] as Hilary Hartwicke\n* [[Bunty Bailey]] as Isabel\n* Cassie Stuart as Enid\n* [[Stephen Lee (actor)|Stephen Lee]] as Ralph Morris\n}}\n==Cancelled sequel==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2014}}\n[[Stuart Gordon]] was, at one point, very interested in directing a sequel to this film. The initial storyline would have followed Judy and Ralph back to [[Boston]] in which Ralph would have indeed married Judy's mother and they would all become a family. Until, one day Judy would receive a box sent from England which would contain the toy makers, Gabriel and Hilary, as dolls. The sequel never happened.\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 62% based on reviews from 13 critics.<ref>{{cite web |title= Dolls (1987) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1006068_dolls |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] }}</ref> \n\n[[Ain't It Cool News]] reviewed the DVD, calling it \"a movie that really stands above the type of film you might expect from this era, with this subject matter.\"<ref>[https://aintitcool.com/node/47172 A Movie A Day: DOLLS (1987) Toys are very loyal and that is a fact.] Ain't It Cool News</ref> [[Roger Ebert]]'s review of the film was mostly negative, writing \"At some point ''Dolls'' remains only an idea, a concept. It doesn't become an engine to shock and involve us,\" though he also conceded that the film \"looks good\" and \"the haunted house looks magnificent.<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19870327/REVIEWS/703270303/1023 Dolls] Roger Ebert</ref> HorrorNews.net's Jeff Colebank listed the toymaking couple as one of the \"13 Best Horror Movie Couples\", stating that Rolfe was \"the creepiest toymaker of them all\".<ref>[https://horrornews.net/30203/list-the-13-best-horror-movie-couples-serial-murder-edition/ The 13 Best Horror Movie Couples (serial murder edition)] HorrorNews.net</ref> [[AllRovi|Allmovie]]'s review of the film was mildly favorable, calling it \"a serious-minded, lovingly-crafted modern fairy tale that only misses classic status by a few clumsy, low-budget moments.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://allmovie.com/movie/dolls-v14236/review |title=Dolls (1987) |author=Robert Firsching |work=[[AllRovi|Allmovie]] |accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n''Dolls'' was released to DVD by [[MGM Home Entertainment]] on September 20, 2005, as a Region 1 widescreen DVD and by the Scream Factory division of Shout! Factory (under license from MGM) on November 11, 2014 as a Region A widescreen Blu-ray.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Killer Toys]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0092906|Dolls}}\n* {{Amg movie|14236|Dolls}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|1006068-dolls|Dolls}}\n* [https://www.ihorror.com/late-to-the-party-dolls-1987/ ''Dolls''] at iHorror\n\n{{Stuart Gordon}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dolls (1987 Film)}}\n[[Category:1987 films]]\n[[Category:1987 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Empire International Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about dolls]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Stuart Gordon]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Hitchhiking in fiction]]\n[[Category:Sentient toys in fiction]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Refimprove|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dolls\n| image          = Dollsposter1987.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Stuart Gordon]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Charles Band]]\n* [[Brian Yuzna]]\n}}\n| writer         = [[Ed Naha]]\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Stephen Lee (actor)|Stephen Lee]]\n* [[Guy Rolfe]]\n* [[Hilary Mason]]\n* Ian Patrick Williams\n* Carolyn Purdy Gordon\n* Cassie Stuart\n* [[Bunty Bailey]]\n* Carrie Lorraine\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* Fuzzbee Morse\n* Victor Spiegel\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Mac Ahlberg]]\n| editing        = Lee Percy\n| distributor    = [[Empire Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1987|4|27|[[Seattle International Film Festival|Seattle Film Festival]]|ref1=<ref name=afi/>|1987|5|22|Los Angeles|ref2=<ref name=afi/>|1987|11|6|New York City|ref3=<ref>{{cite news|work=[[New York Daily News]]|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/41127985/daily_news/|title='Running Man' a Running Joke, But Fun|date=November 18, 1987|via=Newspapers.com|location=New York City, New York}}</ref>}}\n| runtime        = 77 minutes<ref name=afi/>\n| country        = United States<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Film/57605-DOLLS?sid=510a192f-a295-44fc-a9f9-5b7f467d2451&sr=14.645739&cp=1&pos=0|work=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]]|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|location=Los Angeles, California|title=Dolls|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227021918/https://catalog.afi.com/Film/57605-DOLLS?sid=510a192f-a295-44fc-a9f9-5b7f467d2451&sr=14.645739&cp=1&pos=0|archive-date=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $2 million\n| gross          = $3.5 million\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n\n'''''Dolls''''' is a 1987 American [[horror film]] directed by [[Stuart Gordon]], written by [[Ed Naha]], and starring [[Stephen Lee (actor)|Stephen Lee]], [[Guy Rolfe]], [[Hilary Mason]], Ian Patrick Williams, and [[Bunty Bailey]]. Its plot follows six people who seek shelter during a storm in the mansion of an elderly puppetmaker and his wife, only to find that the various puppets and dolls in the home contain the imprisoned spirits of criminals. It was produced by [[Charles Band]] and [[Brian Yuzna]], through Band's [[Empire Pictures]].\n\nThe film was a commercial failure, grossing $3.5 million worldwide against a budget of only $2 million.{{Citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n==Plot==\nA violent [[thunderstorm]] strands a couple and child in the [[gothic fiction|gothic]] English countryside: little Judy, who is traveling with her selfish, uncaring father, David and her rich, callous, arrogant stepmother Rosemary. David only has Judy due to a court order and barely tolerates the little girl's presence, while Rosemary openly dislikes her stepdaughter. After their car is stuck in the mud and the rain begins, they find a mansion. After breaking in, they are found by the owners, a kindly older couple called Gabriel and Hilary Hartwicke. Rosemary threw Judy's beloved [[teddy bear]] into the bushes while out in the rain, so Gabriel gifts her a new [[doll]], Mr. Punch. They are invited to stay and while eating, Isabel and Enid (two British punk rocker hitchhikers) barge in with the person who picked them up, the naive yet good-natured Ralph. Gabriel reveals himself to be a talented toy maker; their house is filled with dolls, puppets, and many other beautifully detailed and handmade toys like Mr. Punch. The Hartwickes invite the stranded travelers to join them to stay as guests until the storm ends and show them to their rooms.\n\nAs it turns out, Isabel has thievery on her mind, and before taking Ralph's wallet and car, she plans on stealing any valuables and antiques the Hartwickes own. Enid just wants to get through the night. Isabel sneaks out and, while casing a room, is brutally attacked by the dolls, who spring to life and beat her before throwing her into the hallway in front of Judy. Unable to speak or even cry for help due to her extensive injuries, she extends her hand in pleading; but before Judy can react in any way, Isabel is dragged off to the attic before her eyes. Judy runs to tell her father and Rosemary, but they accuse her of making up stories and send her away. Judy then goes to Ralph's room to tell him what happened and since she woke him up, he thinks she's dreaming. However, as she turns to leave, he notices blood on her slippers, so he agrees to accompany her. However, on the way downstairs, some of the dolls delay them by tripping Ralph, and he falls down the stairs. He's fine when he gets up, except for a seeming bite mark that he believes came from a rat. They arrive at David and Rosemary's room, and Judy tries to tell him what happened; but they, along with Enid, simply ignore Judy and accuse Ralph of both attacking Isabel and being a pedophile. Upset at the treatment of both her and her new friend, Judy runs off with her father behind her. While looking for Judy, Ralph runs into Gabriel, who tells him that it's not blood but paint that he and Judy stepped in; and Isabel probably just got lost in one of the halls in the large house. Satisfied, he continues his search for Judy, finding her in the kitchen along with Mr. Punch. She continues to try to convince him, but he doesn't believe in the dolls until Mr. Punch himself actually speaks up which shocks both of them. \n\nRosemary is later ambushed and attacked repeatedly by the toys before accidentally leaping to her death (thinking she was jumping over them) out of a window. Enid goes looking for Isabel and finds her almost entirely transformed into a doll version of herself, but still able to attempt to warn her friend to \"go back\". Enid is then attacked by a horde of toys and eventually shot to death by toy soldiers. Rosemary's body has been taken to her bedroom, where, covered in a sheet, her death is not yet noticed by David. A locked room opens itself to Judy and Ralph. Ralph asks if they are Judy's 'little people' whom she spoke of and she informs him that they are. Encountering the dolls gathered together, Ralph ends up getting caught up in a trap the toys set for the other adults and is nearly hurt badly, until Judy convinces them to save him since he is her friend and on their side, too. Afterwards, they are stuck until the dolls decide what to do with them. David, fresh out of the shower, tries to talk to his wife, but finally finds her dead. Believing Ralph murdered her, David prepares to kill him. Now safe from the toys, Judy and Ralph run into the workshop where an angry David finds them. Ralph attempts to tell him what is going on, but David has taken leave of his reason. Ralph has learned the truth about the dolls and refuses to use them to fight, but David doesn't believe and knocks both his daughter and Ralph unconscious when they resist before David is assaulted by Mr. Punch. During their fight, the other dolls drag the unconscious Ralph and Judy away to safety. Mr. Punch is destroyed by David with a mallet after a fierce struggle.\n\nDavid is then confronted by Gabriel and Hilary. It is revealed that Gabriel and Hilary are actually a [[Wizard (paranormal)|wizard]] and [[witch]] couple who see toys as the heart and soul of childhood and believe toys will be around for as long as children (or even those with the hearts of children) want them. They also believe that the bitterness adults feel can turn to love if they surrender to the goodwill that toys provide. They explain that people come to their house every now and then and spend the night. When this happens, they test their visitors to see if they can change or were good from the start, giving them a sporting chance to save themselves. Some people, like Ralph (people who are able to see the love and respect of childhood) and children (like Judy), are saved/spared and leave the house with a much better perspective of life. However, those like David, Rosemary, Isabel, and Enid who refuse to change their ways can never leave, since they must play a new role in the world of children. It is shown that that new role is to become a child's toy when David is (apparently painfully) transformed into a doll to replace Mr. Punch when he attempts to attack the couple.\n\nThe next morning, Ralph and Judy wake up and are convinced by Gabriel and Hilary that the night's events were all just a dream, and receive a letter saying that David is leaving Judy behind because he never was a good father to her and that she will be much happier living in [[Boston]] with her mother. The letter also states that her father and stepmother are moving to another country and changing their names, and have also taken both Enid and Isabel with them, but have left enough money behind for Judy and Ralph to buy plane tickets back to Boston. Ralph and Judy then leave the house together after being bid farewell by Gabriel and Hilary, who invite them to come back whenever they want. As they get into Ralph's car, Judy is overjoyed to find her lost teddy sitting in the front seat, but then decides he would be happier living with the dolls and gives him to the Hartwickes as a gift. As they drive off to the airport, Judy, who has grown quite fond of Ralph, tells him that he will really like her mother and hints to him that if he would like to stay with her and her mother, he could be Judy's new father. Though Ralph does not answer, he expresses interest in the idea.\n\nThe film ends with Mr. and Mrs. Bowers and the punk girls sitting on a shelf as dolls. Just then, another car with [[Dysfunctional family|another family with a set of obnoxious parents]] suddenly arrives, and their car gets stuck in a mud hole yards from the mansion.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast list|\n* Ian Patrick Williams as David Bower\n* Carolyn Purdy Gordon as Rosemary Bower\n* Carrie Lorraine as Judy Bower\n* [[Guy Rolfe]] as Gabriel Hartwicke\n* [[Hilary Mason]] as Hilary Hartwicke\n* [[Bunty Bailey]] as Isabel\n* Cassie Stuart as Enid\n* [[Stephen Lee (actor)|Stephen Lee]] as Ralph Morris\n}}\n==Cancelled sequel==\n{{unreferenced section|date=March 2014}}\n[[Stuart Gordon]] was, at one point, very interested in directing a sequel to this film. The initial storyline would have followed Judy and Ralph back to [[Boston]] in which Ralph would have indeed married Judy's mother and they would all become a family. Until, one day Judy would receive a box sent from England which would contain the toy makers, Gabriel and Hilary, as dolls. The sequel never happened.\n\n==Reception==\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 62% based on reviews from 13 critics.<ref>{{cite web |title= Dolls (1987) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1006068_dolls |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] }}</ref> \n\n[[Ain't It Cool News]] reviewed the DVD, calling it \"a movie that really stands above the type of film you might expect from this era, with this subject matter.\"<ref>[https://aintitcool.com/node/47172 A Movie A Day: DOLLS (1987) Toys are very loyal and that is a fact.] Ain't It Cool News</ref> [[Roger Ebert]]'s review of the film was mostly negative, writing \"At some point ''Dolls'' remains only an idea, a concept. It doesn't become an engine to shock and involve us,\" though he also conceded that the film \"looks good\" and \"the haunted house looks magnificent.<ref>[http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19870327/REVIEWS/703270303/1023 Dolls] Roger Ebert</ref> HorrorNews.net's Jeff Colebank listed the toymaking couple as one of the \"13 Best Horror Movie Couples\", stating that Rolfe was \"the creepiest toymaker of them all\".<ref>[https://horrornews.net/30203/list-the-13-best-horror-movie-couples-serial-murder-edition/ The 13 Best Horror Movie Couples (serial murder edition)] HorrorNews.net</ref> [[AllRovi|Allmovie]]'s review of the film was mildly favorable, calling it \"a serious-minded, lovingly-crafted modern fairy tale that only misses classic status by a few clumsy, low-budget moments.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://allmovie.com/movie/dolls-v14236/review |title=Dolls (1987) |author=Robert Firsching |work=[[AllRovi|Allmovie]] |accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\n''Dolls'' was released to DVD by [[MGM Home Entertainment]] on September 20, 2005, as a Region 1 widescreen DVD and by the Scream Factory division of Shout! Factory (under license from MGM) on November 11, 2014 as a Region A widescreen Blu-ray.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Killer Toys]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0092906|Dolls}}\n* {{Amg movie|14236|Dolls}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|1006068-dolls|Dolls}}\n* [https://www.ihorror.com/late-to-the-party-dolls-1987/ ''Dolls''] at iHorror\n\n{{Stuart Gordon}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dolls (1987 Film)}}\n[[Category:1987 films]]\n[[Category:1987 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:Dark fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Empire International Pictures films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about dolls]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Stuart Gordon]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Hitchhiking in fiction]]\n[[Category:Sentient toys in fiction]]\n[[Category:American supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n", "name_user": "Lairfans12", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dolls_(1987_film)"}
{"title_page": "Roxen (singer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Romanian singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Roxen\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            =\n| image_size       = 250px\n| birth_name       = Larisa Roxana Giurgiu\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|2000|1|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cluj-Napoca]], Romania\n| occupation       = Singer\n| years_active     = 2019\u2013present\n| label            = [[Global Records|Global]]\n| genre            = [[Deep house]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Larisa Roxana Giurgiu''' (born 5 January 2000), known professionally as '''Roxen''', is a Romanian singer signed by [[Global Records]]. She rose to prominence upon being featured on Romanian producer Sickotoy's \"[[You Don't Love Me (Sickotoy song)|You Don't Love Me]]\" (2019), which reached number three in [[Airplay 100 (Romania)|Romania]] and received radio airplay in several other countries. Her debut single, \"[[Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea]]\", eventually peaked atop the national chart. She was scheduled to [[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020|represent Romania]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] with the song \"[[Alcohol You]]\" before the event's [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19)-related cancellation. Roxen was nonetheless internally selected as [[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2021|the country's representative]] for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2021|2021 contest]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[Cluj-Napoca]] on 5 January 2000 as Larisa Roxana Giurgiu, Roxen discovered her passion for music at the age of seven. She also took singing and piano lessons as a child.<ref name=\"dc\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.zi-de-zi.ro/2019/10/20/o-noua-editie-a-festivalului-armonii-muzicale/|title=O noua editie a Festivalului \"Armonii muzicale\"|trans-title=A new edition of the \"Musical Harmonies\" festival|date=20 October 2019|accessdate=11 February 2020|language=Romanian|publisher=Zi de zi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://a1.ro/news/social/roxen-dua-lipa-de-romania-reprezentanta-noastra-la-eurovision-2020-id959370.html|title=Dua Lipa de Rom\u00e2nia, reprezentanta noastr\u0103 la Eurovision 2020|trans-title=The Romanian Dua Lipa is our Eurovision 2020 representative|language=Romanian|date=12 February 2020|accessdate=12 February 2020|publisher=[[Antena 1 (Romania)|Antena 1]]}} ''Note: Play the video.''</ref> Signed by [[Global Records]],<ref name=\"artists\">{{cite news|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/01/romania-tvr-confirms-partnership-with-global-records-for-internal-selection-of-2020-artist/248846/|title=Romania: TVR confirms partnership with Global Records for internal selection of 2020 artist|publisher=[[Wiwibloggs]]|date=1 February 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|author=Gallagher, Robyn}}</ref> she was featured on Romanian producer Sickotoy's \"[[You Don't Love Me (Sickotoy song)|You Don't Love Me]]\" in August 2019.<ref name=\"youdontloveme\"/> The single attained commercial success in Romania, reaching number three on the country's [[Airplay 100 (Romania)|Airplay 100]] chart,<ref name=\"Romania\"/> and being playslisted by radio stations in several territories including France, United States, Russia and Spain.<ref name=\"dc\"/> Her debut single \"[[Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea]]\" was released in the November of the same year and peaked at number one in Romania.<ref name=\"Romania\"/> \n\nIn early February 2020, it was reported that Roxen was one of three artists shortlisted to [[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest|represent Romania]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]]; broadcaster [[Romanian Television]] (TVR) had collaborated with Global Records for the selection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://escbubble.com/2020/02/romania-will-reveal-the-representative-on-10th-february/|title=Romania will reveal the representative on 10th February|publisher=ESCBubble|date=4 February 2020|accessdate=4 February 2020|author=Muntean, Marco}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tvr.ro/tvr-i-global-records-parteneri-pentru-eurovision-song-contest-2020_26414.html#view|title=TVR \u0219i Global Records, parteneri pentru Eurovision Song Contest 2020|trans-title=TVR and Global Records, partners for the 2020 Eurovision Song Contest|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=31 January 2020|language=Romanian|publisher=[[Romanian Television]]}}</ref> On 11 February, she was revealed as the Romanian representative.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/video/roxen-will-represent-romania-at-the-eurovision-song-contest-2020|title=Roxen will represent Romania at the Eurovision Song Contest 2020|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=11 February 2020|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Her five songs for ''[[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020#Selec\u021bia Na\u021bional\u0103 2020|Selec\u021bia Na\u021bional\u0103]]''\u2014\"[[Alcohol You]]\", \"Beautiful Disaster\", \"Cherry Red\", \"Colors\" and \"Storm\"\u2014were released on 21 February 2020.<ref name=\"songssn\">{{cite news|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/21/romanias-roxen-releases-snippets-of-her-five-songs-up-for-contention-for-eurovision-2020/250352/|title=Romania\u2019s Roxen releases snippets of her five songs in contention for Eurovision 2020|publisher=[[Wiwibloggs]]|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=21 February 2020|author=Percy, Lucy}}</ref> \"Alcohol You\" emerged as the winner of the national final.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/01/roxen-to-sing-alcohol-you-in-rotterdam/|title=Roxen to sing \u201cAlcohol You\u201d in Rotterdam!|publisher=ESCXtra|author=Luukela, Sami|date=1 March 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> However, on 18 March, the [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) announced the cancellation of the Eurovision Song Contest 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[China]] and its spread to other countries.<ref name=\"cancellation\">{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/eurovision-2020-in-rotterdam-is-cancelled|title=Eurovision 2020 in Rotterdam is cancelled|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Although TVR had considered sending \"Alcohol You\" to participate in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2021]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/18/roxen-and-tvr-release-statements-regarding-eurovision/|title=Roxen and TVR release statements regarding Eurovision|publisher=ESCXtra|author=Luukela, Sami|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> EBU soon after announced that intended 2020 entries were not eligible for the following year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/intention-to-honour-eurovision-2020-songs-artists|title=Intention to honour Eurovision 2020 songs and artists|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> Roxen was nonetheless internally selected for the 2021 contest.<ref name=\"roxen 2021\">{{cite news|url=http://eurovision.tvr.ro/2020/tvr-a-decis-roxen-va-reprezenta-romania-la-eurovision-song-contest-2021_26787.html|title=TVR a decis: Roxen va reprezenta Romania la Eurovision Song Contest 2021|language=Romanian|publisher=[[Romanian Television]]|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|trans-title=TVR has decided: Roxen will represent Romania at the Eurovision Song Contest 2021}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nRoxen's primary genre is [[deep house]].<ref name=\"dc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dcnews.ro/roxen-cucereste-topurile-muzicale-melodiile-ei-o-terapie_727411.html|title=Roxen cucere\u0219te topurile muzicale!|trans-title=Roxen attains success on music charts!|language=Romanian|date=3 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020|publisher=DC News|author=Scutaru, Cristina}}</ref> Multiple observers have compared her music style and appearance to that of [[Dua Lipa]] and [[Billie Eilish]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.unica.ro/video/exclusiv-roxen-ne-spune-povestea-vietii-ei-299682|title=Roxen ne spune povestea vie\u021bii ei|trans-title=Roxen tells us the story of her life|work=Unica|date=7 January 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> In an interview, Roxen cited [[Beyonc\u00e9]] as one of her major musical inspirations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yiTeZw93xTM|title=Roxen, reprezentantul Romaniei la Eurovision, in de 10X Romania alaturi de Razvan Petre|trans-title=Roxen, Romania's Eurovision representative, on 10X Romania with Razvan Petre|date=6 March 2020|accessdate=7 March 2020|language=Romanian|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Singles===\n\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[Airplay 100 (Romania)|ROM]]<br><ref name=\"Romania\">For peak positions in Romania:\n*For \"You Don't Love Me\": {{cite news|url=https://www.unsitedemuzica.ro/topuri/Top-Airplay-100-Fie-iarna-fie-vant-pe-Strazile-din-Bucuresti-ne-luam-avant-p8766|title=Top Airplay 100 - Fie iarn\u0103, fie v\u00e2nt, pe \"Str\u0103zile din Bucure\u015fti\" ne lu\u0103m av\u00e2nt!|trans-title=Top Airplay 100 \u2013 Be it winter or wind, on the streets of Bucharest we are thriving!|author=Arvunescu, Victor|date=25 November 2019|accessdate=25 November 2019|language=Romanian|publisher=Un site de muzic\u0103}}\n*For \"Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea\": {{cite news|url=https://www.unsitedemuzica.ro/topuri/Top-Airplay-100-Nu-mai-ajunge-la-Eurovision-dar-a-ajuns-pe-primul-loc-p9545|title=Top Airplay 100 - Nu mai ajunge la Eurovision, dar a ajuns pe primul loc|trans-title=Top Airplay 100 \u2013 She will not go to Eurovision but reached number one|author=Arvunescu, Victor|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|language=Romanian|publisher=Un site de muzic\u0103}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea]]\"<ref name=\"dragostea\">{{cite news|url=https://music.apple.com/ro/album/ce-%C5%A3i-c%C3%A2nt%C4%83-dragostea-single/1488124337|title=Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea - Single by Roxen on iTunes|date=12 November 2019|accessdate=5 February 2020|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2019\n| 1\n| rowspan=\"3\" {{N/A|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Don't Care\"<ref name=\"idontcare\">{{cite news|url=https://music.apple.com/ro/album/i-dont-care-single/1490232544|title=I Don't Care - Single by Roxen on iTunes|date=2 December 2019|accessdate=5 February 2020|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}</ref>\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Alcohol You]]\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2020\n| \u2014\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"font-size:9pt\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a title that did not chart, or was not released in that territory.\n\n|}\n\n====As featured artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[Airplay 100 (Romania)|ROM]]<br><ref name=\"Romania\"/>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[IFPI|BUL]]<br><ref name=\"Bulgaria\">{{cite news|url=https://www.prophon.org/charts/15-nov-2019|title=PROPHON \u2013 Charts|publisher=[[IFPI|PROPHON]]|accessdate=7 February 2020|date=15 November 2019|language=Bulgarian}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[You Don't Love Me (Sickotoy song)|You Don't Love Me]]\"<ref name=\"youdontloveme\">{{cite news|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/you-dont-love-me-feat-roxen-single/1476279462|title=You Don't Love Me (feat. Roxen) - Single by Sickotoy on iTunes|date=12 August 2019|accessdate=5 February 2020|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}</ref><br/>{{small|(Sickotoy featuring Roxen)}}\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2019\n| 3 || 7\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Over and Over\"<ref name=\"overandover\">{{cite news|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/over-and-over-feat-roxen-single/1500721332|title=Over and Over (feat. Roxen) - Single by PAX Paradise Auxiliary on iTunes|date=17 March 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}</ref><br/>{{small|(PAX featuring Roxen)}}\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2020\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"font-size:9pt\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a title that did not chart, or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n====Promotional singles====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Beautiful Disaster\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2020\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Cherry Red\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Colors\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Storm\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14em;\"| Title{{efn| group=upper-alpha|Solely lists official music videos.}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 2em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 8em;\"| Lead performer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 11em;\"| Guest performer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 13em;\"| Director(s)\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"You Don't Love Me\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.infomusic.ro/videoclip/sickotoy-feat-roxen-you-dont-love-me/|title=Videoclip oficial: Sickotoy feat. Roxen - You Don't Love Me|publisher=InfoMusic|date=4 September 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020|author=Chiril\u0103, Raluca}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2019\n|Sickotoy\n|Roxen\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Raluca Netca\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YRUJEhhQHMQ|title=Roxen - Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea {{!}} Official Video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=12 November 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}} ''Note: Open the description for credits.''</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Roxen\n|rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"I Don't Care\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ro6j7I0-Pxw|title=Roxen - I Don't Care (The Session - Official Video)|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=2 December 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}} ''Note: Open the description for credits.''</ref>\n|\u0218erban Racoviteanu\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Over and Over\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K6xWEgkJsCU|title=PAX (Paradise Auxiliary) feat. Roxen - Over and Over - Official Video |publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}} ''Note: Open the description for credits.''</ref>\n|2020\n|PAX\n|Roxen\n|Alex Mure\u015fan\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{Succession box\n|before=[[Ester Peony]]<br>with \"[[On a Sunday]]\"\n|title=[[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest]]|\n years=[[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020]]|\n after= ''Incumbent''\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2020 |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Romanian Eurovision Song Contest entrants]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest entrants of 2020]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest entrants of 2021]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Romania]]\n[[Category:Deep house musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Cluj-Napoca]]\n[[Category:Romanian female singers]]\n[[Category:Global Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Romanian singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Roxen\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            =\n| image_size       = 250px\n| birth_name       = Larisa Roxana Giurgiu\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|2000|1|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cluj-Napoca]], Romania\n| occupation       = Singer\n| years_active     = 2019\u2013present\n| label            = [[Global Records|Global]]\n| genre            = [[Deep house]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Larisa Roxana Giurgiu''' (born 5 January 2000), known professionally as '''Roxen''', is a Romanian singer signed by [[Global Records]]. She rose to prominence upon being featured on Romanian producer Sickotoy's \"[[You Don't Love Me (Sickotoy song)|You Don't Love Me]]\" (2019), which reached number three in [[Airplay 100 (Romania)|Romania]] and received radio airplay in several other countries. Her debut single, \"[[Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea]]\", eventually peaked atop the national chart. She was scheduled to [[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020|represent Romania]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]] with the song \"[[Alcohol You]]\" before the event's [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19)-related cancellation. Roxen was nonetheless internally selected as [[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2021|the country's representative]] for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2021|2021 contest]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn in [[Cluj-Napoca]] on 5 January 2000 as Larisa Roxana Giurgiu, Roxen discovered her passion for music at the age of seven. She also took singing and piano lessons as a child.<ref name=\"dc\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.zi-de-zi.ro/2019/10/20/o-noua-editie-a-festivalului-armonii-muzicale/|title=O noua editie a Festivalului \"Armonii muzicale\"|trans-title=A new edition of the \"Musical Harmonies\" festival|date=20 October 2019|accessdate=11 February 2020|language=Romanian|publisher=Zi de zi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://a1.ro/news/social/roxen-dua-lipa-de-romania-reprezentanta-noastra-la-eurovision-2020-id959370.html|title=Dua Lipa de Rom\u00e2nia, reprezentanta noastr\u0103 la Eurovision 2020|trans-title=The Romanian Dua Lipa is our Eurovision 2020 representative|language=Romanian|date=12 February 2020|accessdate=12 February 2020|publisher=[[Antena 1 (Romania)|Antena 1]]}} ''Note: Play the video.''</ref> Signed by [[Global Records]],<ref name=\"artists\">{{cite news|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/01/romania-tvr-confirms-partnership-with-global-records-for-internal-selection-of-2020-artist/248846/|title=Romania: TVR confirms partnership with Global Records for internal selection of 2020 artist|publisher=[[Wiwibloggs]]|date=1 February 2020|accessdate=1 February 2020|author=Gallagher, Robyn}}</ref> she was featured on Romanian producer Sickotoy's \"[[You Don't Love Me (Sickotoy song)|You Don't Love Me]]\" in August 2019.<ref name=\"youdontloveme\"/> The single attained commercial success in Romania, reaching number three on the country's [[Airplay 100 (Romania)|Airplay 100]] chart,<ref name=\"Romania\"/> and being playslisted by radio stations in several territories including France, United States, Russia and Spain.<ref name=\"dc\"/> Her debut single \"[[Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea]]\" was released in the November of the same year and peaked at number one in Romania.<ref name=\"Romania\"/> \n\nIn early February 2020, it was reported that Roxen was one of three artists shortlisted to [[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest|represent Romania]] at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]]; broadcaster [[Romanian Television]] (TVR) had collaborated with Global Records for the selection.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://escbubble.com/2020/02/romania-will-reveal-the-representative-on-10th-february/|title=Romania will reveal the representative on 10th February|publisher=ESCBubble|date=4 February 2020|accessdate=4 February 2020|author=Muntean, Marco}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tvr.ro/tvr-i-global-records-parteneri-pentru-eurovision-song-contest-2020_26414.html#view|title=TVR \u0219i Global Records, parteneri pentru Eurovision Song Contest 2020|trans-title=TVR and Global Records, partners for the 2020 Eurovision Song Contest|date=31 January 2020|accessdate=31 January 2020|language=Romanian|publisher=[[Romanian Television]]}}</ref> On 11 February, she was revealed as the Romanian representative.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/video/roxen-will-represent-romania-at-the-eurovision-song-contest-2020|title=Roxen will represent Romania at the Eurovision Song Contest 2020|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=11 February 2020|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> Her five songs for ''[[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest 2020#Selec\u021bia Na\u021bional\u0103 2020|Selec\u021bia Na\u021bional\u0103]]''\u2014\"[[Alcohol You]]\", \"Beautiful Disaster\", \"Cherry Red\", \"Colors\" and \"Storm\"\u2014were released on 21 February 2020.<ref name=\"songssn\">{{cite news|url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/21/romanias-roxen-releases-snippets-of-her-five-songs-up-for-contention-for-eurovision-2020/250352/|title=Romania\u2019s Roxen releases snippets of her five songs in contention for Eurovision 2020|publisher=[[Wiwibloggs]]|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=21 February 2020|author=Percy, Lucy}}</ref> \"Alcohol You\" emerged as the winner of the national final.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/01/roxen-to-sing-alcohol-you-in-rotterdam/|title=Roxen to sing \u201cAlcohol You\u201d in Rotterdam!|publisher=ESCXtra|author=Luukela, Sami|date=1 March 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> However, on 18 March, the [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) announced the cancellation of the Eurovision Song Contest 2020 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of the [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[China]] and its spread to other countries.<ref name=\"cancellation\">{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/eurovision-2020-in-rotterdam-is-cancelled|title=Eurovision 2020 in Rotterdam is cancelled|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Although TVR had considered sending \"Alcohol You\" to participate in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2021]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/18/roxen-and-tvr-release-statements-regarding-eurovision/|title=Roxen and TVR release statements regarding Eurovision|publisher=ESCXtra|author=Luukela, Sami|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> EBU soon after announced that intended 2020 entries were not eligible for the following year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/intention-to-honour-eurovision-2020-songs-artists|title=Intention to honour Eurovision 2020 songs and artists|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> Roxen was nonetheless internally selected for the 2021 contest.<ref name=\"roxen 2021\">{{cite news|url=http://eurovision.tvr.ro/2020/tvr-a-decis-roxen-va-reprezenta-romania-la-eurovision-song-contest-2021_26787.html|title=TVR a decis: Roxen va reprezenta Romania la Eurovision Song Contest 2021|language=Romanian|publisher=[[Romanian Television]]|date=31 March 2020|accessdate=31 March 2020|trans-title=TVR has decided: Roxen will represent Romania at the Eurovision Song Contest 2021}}</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\nRoxen's primary genre is [[deep house]].<ref name=\"dc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.dcnews.ro/roxen-cucereste-topurile-muzicale-melodiile-ei-o-terapie_727411.html|title=Roxen cucere\u0219te topurile muzicale!|trans-title=Roxen attains success on music charts!|language=Romanian|date=3 February 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020|publisher=DC News|author=Scutaru, Cristina}}</ref> Multiple observers have compared her music style and appearance to that of [[Dua Lipa]] and [[Billie Eilish]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.unica.ro/video/exclusiv-roxen-ne-spune-povestea-vietii-ei-299682|title=Roxen ne spune povestea vie\u021bii ei|trans-title=Roxen tells us the story of her life|work=Unica|date=7 January 2020|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> In an interview, Roxen cited [[Beyonc\u00e9]] as one of her major musical inspirations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yiTeZw93xTM|title=Roxen, reprezentantul Romaniei la Eurovision, in de 10X Romania alaturi de Razvan Petre|trans-title=Roxen, Romania's Eurovision representative, on 10X Romania with Razvan Petre|date=6 March 2020|accessdate=7 March 2020|language=Romanian|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Singles===\n\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[Airplay 100 (Romania)|ROM]]<br><ref name=\"Romania\">For peak positions in Romania:\n*For \"You Don't Love Me\": {{cite news|url=https://www.unsitedemuzica.ro/topuri/Top-Airplay-100-Fie-iarna-fie-vant-pe-Strazile-din-Bucuresti-ne-luam-avant-p8766|title=Top Airplay 100 - Fie iarn\u0103, fie v\u00e2nt, pe \"Str\u0103zile din Bucure\u015fti\" ne lu\u0103m av\u00e2nt!|trans-title=Top Airplay 100 \u2013 Be it winter or wind, on the streets of Bucharest we are thriving!|author=Arvunescu, Victor|date=25 November 2019|accessdate=25 November 2019|language=Romanian|publisher=Un site de muzic\u0103}}\n*For \"Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea\": {{cite news|url=https://www.unsitedemuzica.ro/topuri/Top-Airplay-100-Nu-mai-ajunge-la-Eurovision-dar-a-ajuns-pe-primul-loc-p9545|title=Top Airplay 100 - Nu mai ajunge la Eurovision, dar a ajuns pe primul loc|trans-title=Top Airplay 100 \u2013 She will not go to Eurovision but reached number one|author=Arvunescu, Victor|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020|language=Romanian|publisher=Un site de muzic\u0103}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea]]\"<ref name=\"dragostea\">{{cite news|url=https://music.apple.com/ro/album/ce-%C5%A3i-c%C3%A2nt%C4%83-dragostea-single/1488124337|title=Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea - Single by Roxen on iTunes|date=12 November 2019|accessdate=5 February 2020|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2019\n| 1\n| rowspan=\"3\" {{N/A|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"I Don't Care\"<ref name=\"idontcare\">{{cite news|url=https://music.apple.com/ro/album/i-dont-care-single/1490232544|title=I Don't Care - Single by Roxen on iTunes|date=2 December 2019|accessdate=5 February 2020|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}</ref>\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Alcohol You]]\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2020\n| \u2014\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"font-size:9pt\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a title that did not chart, or was not released in that territory.\n\n|}\n\n====As featured artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[Airplay 100 (Romania)|ROM]]<br><ref name=\"Romania\"/>\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[IFPI|BUL]]<br><ref name=\"Bulgaria\">{{cite news|url=https://www.prophon.org/charts/15-nov-2019|title=PROPHON \u2013 Charts|publisher=[[IFPI|PROPHON]]|accessdate=7 February 2020|date=15 November 2019|language=Bulgarian}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[You Don't Love Me (Sickotoy song)|You Don't Love Me]]\"<ref name=\"youdontloveme\">{{cite news|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/you-dont-love-me-feat-roxen-single/1476279462|title=You Don't Love Me (feat. Roxen) - Single by Sickotoy on iTunes|date=12 August 2019|accessdate=5 February 2020|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}</ref><br/>{{small|(Sickotoy featuring Roxen)}}\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2019\n| 3 || 7\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Over and Over\"<ref name=\"overandover\">{{cite news|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/over-and-over-feat-roxen-single/1500721332|title=Over and Over (feat. Roxen) - Single by PAX Paradise Auxiliary on iTunes|date=17 March 2019|accessdate=25 March 2020|publisher=[[iTunes Store]]}}</ref><br/>{{small|(PAX featuring Roxen)}}\n| rowspan=\"1\"|2020\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"font-size:9pt\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a title that did not chart, or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n====Promotional singles====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Beautiful Disaster\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2020\n| rowspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Non-album singles}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Cherry Red\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Colors\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Storm\"<ref name=\"songssn\"/>\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 14em;\"| Title{{efn| group=upper-alpha|Solely lists official music videos.}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 2em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 8em;\"| Lead performer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 11em;\"| Guest performer(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: 13em;\"| Director(s)\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"You Don't Love Me\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.infomusic.ro/videoclip/sickotoy-feat-roxen-you-dont-love-me/|title=Videoclip oficial: Sickotoy feat. Roxen - You Don't Love Me|publisher=InfoMusic|date=4 September 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020|author=Chiril\u0103, Raluca}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|2019\n|Sickotoy\n|Roxen\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Raluca Netca\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YRUJEhhQHMQ|title=Roxen - Ce-\u021bi c\u00e2nt\u0103 dragostea {{!}} Official Video|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=12 November 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}} ''Note: Open the description for credits.''</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Roxen\n|rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A|None}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"I Don't Care\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ro6j7I0-Pxw|title=Roxen - I Don't Care (The Session - Official Video)|publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=2 December 2019|accessdate=15 February 2020}} ''Note: Open the description for credits.''</ref>\n|\u0218erban Racoviteanu\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|\"Over and Over\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K6xWEgkJsCU|title=PAX (Paradise Auxiliary) feat. Roxen - Over and Over - Official Video |publisher=[[YouTube]]|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=25 March 2020}} ''Note: Open the description for credits.''</ref>\n|2020\n|PAX\n|Roxen\n|Alex Mure\u015fan\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{Succession box\n|before=[[Ester Peony]]<br>with \"[[On a Sunday]]\"\n|title=[[Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest]]|\n years=[[Eurovision Song Contest 2020|2020]]|\n after= ''Incumbent''\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Romania in the Eurovision Song Contest |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Eurovision Song Contest 2020 |state=autocollapse}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Romanian Eurovision Song Contest entrants]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest entrants of 2020]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Romania]]\n[[Category:Deep house musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Cluj-Napoca]]\n[[Category:Romanian female singers]]\n[[Category:Global Records artists]]\n", "name_user": "Grk1011", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:21 cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roxen_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "Antefungivoridae", "text_new": "{{short description|Family of flies}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil range|Pliensbachian|Aptian}}\n| image =\n| display_parents = 3\n| taxon = Antefungivoridae\n}}\n\n'''Antefungivoridae''' is an extinct family of fungus gnats and gall midges in the order [[Diptera]]. There are about 9 genera and more than 40 described species in Antefungivoridae.<ref name=gbif/><ref name=paleo/><ref name=Greenwalt2019/>\n\n==Genera==\nThese nine genera belong to the family Antefungivoridae:\n* \u2020 ''[[Antefungivora]]'' <small>Rohdendorf, 1938</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Antiquamedia]]'' <small>Rohdendorf, 1938</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Aortomima]]'' <small>Zhang, Zhang, Liu & Shangguan, 1986</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Baishuilingella]]'' <small>Lin, 1980</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Lycoriomimodes]]'' <small>Rodendorf, 1946</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Mimallactoneura]]'' <small>Rodendorf, 1946</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Paralycoriomima]]'' <small>Rodendorf, 1946</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Pleciomima]]'' <small>Rohdendorf, 1938</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Sciaromima]]'' <small>Kovalev, 1990</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=gbif>\n{{Cite web| title=Antefungivoridae\n| url=https://www.gbif.org/species/4795454\n| website=GBIF\n| accessdate=2019-06-06\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=paleo>\n{{Cite web| title=The Paleobiology Database, family Antefungivoridae\n| url=https://paleobiodb.org/classic/basicTaxonInfo?taxon_no=254077\n| accessdate=2019-06-06\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Greenwalt2019>\n{{Cite web\n| accessdate = 2019-06-06\n| title = Fungus Gnats Online\n| date = 2019\n| last1 = Greenwalt | first1 = D.\n| last2 = Kj\u00e6randsen | first2 = J.\n| url = http://sciaroidea.info/taxonomy/40255\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q19371730}}\n\n[[Category:Nematocera]]\n[[Category:Nematocera families|\u2020Antefungivoridae]]\n[[Category:Extinct insect families]]\n\n\n{{Paleo-arthropod-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Family of flies}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil range|Pliensbachian|Aptian}}\n| image =\n| display_parents = 3\n| taxon = Antefungivoridae\n}}\n\n'''Antefungivoridae''' is an extinct family of fungus gnats and gall midges in the order [[Diptera]]. There are about 9 genera and more than 40 described species in Antefungivoridae.<ref name=gbif/><ref name=paleo/><ref name=Greenwalt2019/>\n\n==Genera==\nThese nine genera belong to the family Antefungivoridae:\n* \u2020 ''[[Antefungivora]]'' <small>Rohdendorf, 1938</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Antiquamedia]]'' <small>Rohdendorf, 1938</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Aortomima]]'' <small>Zhang, Zhang, Liu & Shangguan, 1986</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Baishuilingella]]'' <small>Lin, 1980</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Lycoriomimodes]]'' <small>Rodendorf, 1946</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Mimallactoneura]]'' <small>Rodendorf, 1946</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Paralycoriomima]]'' <small>Rodendorf, 1946</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Pleciomima]]'' <small>Rohdendorf, 1938</small>\n* \u2020 ''[[Sciaromima]]'' <small>Kovalev, 1990</small>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=gbif>\n{{Cite web| title=Antefungivoridae\n| url=https://www.gbif.org/species/4795454\n| website=GBIF\n| accessdate=2019-06-06\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=paleo>\n{{Cite web| title=The Paleobiology Database, family Antefungivoridae\n| url=https://paleobiodb.org/classic/basicTaxonInfo?taxon_no=254077\n| accessdate=2019-06-06\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Greenwalt2019>\n{{Cite web\n| accessdate = 2019-06-06\n| title = Fungus Gnats Online\n| date = 2019\n| last1 = Greenwalt | first1 = D.\n| last2 = Kj\u00e6randsen | first2 = J.\n| url = http://sciaroidea.info/taxonomy/40255\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q19371730}}\n\n[[Category:Nematocera]]\n[[Category:Prehistoric insect families]]\n\n\n{{Paleo-arthropod-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dyanega", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix cats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antefungivoridae"}
{"title_page": "Mendoza, Argentina", "text_new": "{{For|the Argentine wine region|Mendoza wine}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Mendoza\n| official_name                   = City of Mendoza<br/>{{native name|es|Ciudad de Mendoza}}\n| native_name                     = Huentota\n| settlement_type                 = [[City]]\n| image_skyline                   = Downtown Mendoza.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Downtown Mendoza\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = Escudo Departamental Mendoza.png\n| pushpin_map                     = Argentina\n| pushpin_label_position          = bottom\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in [[Argentina]]\n| pushpin_mapsize                 = 200\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|Argentina}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Provinces of Argentina|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|Mendoza}}\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Departments of Argentina|Department]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Capital Department, Mendoza|Capital]]\n| established_title               = Settled\n| established_date                = {{Start date and age|1561}}\n| founder                         = Pedro del Castillo\n| named_for                       = [[Garc\u00eda Hurtado de Mendoza, 5th Marquis of Ca\u00f1ete]]\n| government_type                 = \n| leader_title                    = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name                     = Rodolfo Alejandro Suarez ([[Radical Civic Union|UCR]])\n| area_magnitude                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_total_km2                  = 54\n| elevation_m                     = 746.5\n| population_as_of                = 2010 census\n| population_urban                = 115,041\n| population_metro                = 1,055,679\n| population_est                  = \n| population_est_as_of            = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_density_km2          = 2055.4\n| population_blank1_title         = [[Demonym]]\n| population_blank1               = Mendocenean (Mendocino/-a Spanish)\n| timezone1                       = [[Time in Argentina|ART]]\n| utc_offset1                     = -3\n| timezone1_DST                   = <!--NO-->\n| utc_offset1_DST                 = <!--NO-->\n| postal_code_type                = [[Argentine postal code|CPA Base]]\n| postal_code                     = [[ISO 3166-2:AR|M]] 5500\n| area_code                       = +[[Telephone numbers in Argentina|54]] 261\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|32|53|S|68|49|W|region:AR|display=inline,title}}\n| blank_name                      = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n| blank_info                      = [[Desert climate#Cold desert climates|BWk]]\n| website                         = [http://www.ciudaddemendoza.gov.ar www.ciudaddemendoza.gov.ar]\n}}\n\n'''Mendoza''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u025b|n|\u02c8|d|o\u028a|z|\u0259}}, {{IPA-es|men\u02c8dosa|am}}), officially the '''City of Mendoza''' ({{lang-es|Ciudad de Mendoza}}) is the capital of the [[Provinces of Argentina|province]] of [[Mendoza Province|Mendoza]] in [[Argentina]]. It is located in the northern-central part of the province, in a region of foothills and high plains, on the eastern side of the [[Andes]]. As of the {{census-ar|2010}}, Mendoza had a population of 115,041 with a metropolitan population of 1,055,679, making [[Greater Mendoza]] the fourth largest census metropolitan area in the country.\n\n[[National Route 7 (Argentina)|Ruta Nacional 7]], the major road running between [[Buenos Aires]] and [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]], runs through Mendoza. The city is a frequent stopover for climbers on their way to [[Aconcagua]] (the highest mountain in the Western and Southern Hemispheres) and for [[adventure travel]]ers interested in [[mountaineering]], [[hiking]], [[horse riding]], [[rafting]], and other sports. In the winter, [[ski]]ers come to the city for easy access to the Andes.\n\nTwo of the main industries of the Mendoza area are [[olive oil]] production and [[Argentine wine]]. The region around Greater Mendoza is the largest wine-producing area in [[South America]]. As such, Mendoza is one of the nine Great Wine Capitals,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.greatwinecapitals.com/ |title=The Great Wine Capitals |access-date=2019-09-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807002916/http://www.greatwinecapitals.com/ |archive-date=2019-08-07 |url-status=live }}</ref> and the city is an emerging [[enotourism]] destination and base for exploring the region's hundreds of wineries located along the [[Argentina Wine Route]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Traza de la segunda fundaci\u00f3n de Mendoza, 1562.jpg|left|thumb|Print of the second foundation of Mendoza, 1562]]\nOn March 2, 1561, [[Pedro del Castillo]] founded the city and named it ''Ciudad de Mendoza del Nuevo Valle de La Rioja'' after the governor of [[Chile]], Don [[Garc\u00eda Hurtado de Mendoza, 5th Marquis of Ca\u00f1ete|Garc\u00eda Hurtado de Mendoza]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.welcomeargentina.com/mendoza/history.html |title=welcomeargentina.com: Land of the good wine |access-date=2007-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018111852/http://welcomeargentina.com/mendoza/history.html |archive-date=2007-10-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Before the 1560s the area was populated by tribes known as the [[Huarpe]]s and [[Puelche]]s. The Huarpes devised a system of irrigation that was later developed by the Spanish. This allowed for an increase in population that might not have otherwise occurred. The system is still evident today in the wide trenches ([[acequia]]s), which run along all city streets, watering the approximately 100,000 trees that line every street in Mendoza.\n\nIt is estimated that fewer than 80 Spanish settlers lived in the area before 1600, but later prosperity increased due to the use of indigenous and slave labor, and the [[Jesuits|Jesuit]] presence in the region. When nearby rivers were tapped as a source of irrigation in 1788 agricultural production increased. The extra revenues generated from this, and the ensuing additional trade with [[Buenos Aires]], no doubt led to the creation of the state of [[Cuyo (Argentina)|Cuyo]] in 1813 with [[Jos\u00e9 de San Mart\u00edn]] as governor. It was from Mendoza that San Mart\u00edn and other Argentinian and Chilean patriots organized the army with which they won the independence of [[Chilean Independence|Chile]] and [[Peruvian War of Independence|Peru]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mainlesson.com/display.php?author=morris&book=samerican&story=hannibal |title=Morris Charles \u2013 The Hannibal of the Andes and the Freedom of Chile |access-date=2007-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610043606/http://www.mainlesson.com/display.php?author=morris&book=samerican&story=hannibal |archive-date=2011-06-10 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMendoza suffered [[1861 Mendoza earthquake|a severe earthquake]] in 1861 that killed at least 5,000 people. The city was rebuilt, incorporating innovative urban designs that would better tolerate such seismic activity. Mendoza was rebuilt with large squares and wider streets and sidewalks than any other city in Argentina. Avenue [[Bartolom\u00e9 Mitre]] and additional small squares are examples of that design. Tourism, [[wine]] production, and more recently the exploitation of hard commodities such as oil<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://aapgbull.geoscienceworld.org/cgi/content/abstract/28/10/1455 |title=Baldwin Harry L. \u2013 Tupungato oil field |access-date=2007-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721224740/http://aapgbull.geoscienceworld.org/cgi/content/abstract/28/10/1455 |archive-date=2011-07-21 |url-status=live }}</ref> and uranium<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wise-uranium.org/upsam.html#SIERRAPINTADA |title=New uranium mining projects |access-date=2007-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030061558/http://www.wise-uranium.org/upsam.html#SIERRAPINTADA |archive-date=2007-10-30 |url-status=live }}</ref> ensure Mendoza's status as a key regional center.\n\nImportant suburbs such as [[Godoy Cruz, Mendoza|Godoy Cruz]], [[Guaymall\u00e9n Department|Guaymall\u00e9n]], [[Las Heras, Mendoza|Las Heras]], [[Luj\u00e1n de Cuyo]] and [[Maip\u00fa, Mendoza|Maip\u00fa]] have in recent decades far outpaced the city proper in population. Comprising half the metro population of 212,000 in 1947, these suburbs grew to nearly \u215e of the total metro area of over 1,000,000 by 2015, making Mendoza the most dispersed metro area in Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|title=Encuesta Permanente de Hogares|url=http://www.indec.gov.ar/uploads/informesdeprensa/EPH_cont_3trim15.pdf|page=3|publisher=Indec|date=23 August 2015|access-date=2 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818102123/https://www.indec.gov.ar/uploads/informesdeprensa/EPH_cont_3trim15.pdf|archive-date=18 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nMendoza has several museums, including the Museo Cornelio Moyano, a natural history museum, and the Museo del \u00c1rea Fundacional (Historical Regional Foundation Museum) on Pedro del Castillo Square. The Museo Nacional del Vino (National Wine Museum), focusing on the history of winemaking in the area, is {{convert|17|km|0|abbr=off}} southeast of Mendoza in [[Maip\u00fa, Mendoza|Maip\u00fa]]. The Casa de Fader, a [[historic house museum]], is an 1890 mansion once home to artist [[Fernando Fader]] in nearby Mayor Drummond, {{convert|14|km|0|abbr=off}} south of Mendoza. The mansion is home to many of the artist's paintings.\n\n[[Fiesta Nacional de la Vendimia|The Fiesta Nacional de la Vendimia]] (The National Grape Harvest Festival) occurs in early March each year. Part of the festivities include a [[Beauty contest|beauty pageant]], where 17 beauty queens from each [[Departments of Argentina|department]] of [[Mendoza Province]] compete, and one winner is selected by a panel of about 50 judges. The queen of Mendoza city's department does not compete and acts as host for the other queens.\n\nIn 2008, ''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]'' listed Mendoza as one of the top 10 historic destinations in the world.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://traveler.nationalgeographic.com/2008/11/historic-destinations-rated/list-text |title=''National Geographic'' \u2013 2008 Ranking of Historic Places |access-date=2008-11-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081027093556/http://traveler.nationalgeographic.com/2008/11/historic-destinations-rated/list-text |archive-date=2008-10-27 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nMendoza has a number of universities, including the major [[Universidad Nacional de Cuyo]], as well as [[Universidad de Mendoza|University of Mendoza]], a branch of Universidad Congreso, [[Aconcagua University]], UTN (Universidad Tecnologica Nacional) and Champagnat University.\n\nMendoza is a popular place to learn Spanish, and there are a number of Spanish language schools, including Intercultural, Green Fields and SIMA.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spanishinmendozaargentina.greenash.net.au/ |title=SIMA: Spanish in Mendoza Argentina |publisher=Spanishinmendozaargentina.greenash.net.au |accessdate=2013-03-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130409080558/http://spanishinmendozaargentina.greenash.net.au/ |archive-date=2013-04-09 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Urban structure==\nThe city is centered around Plaza Independencia (Independence Plaza) with Avenida [[Domingo Faustino Sarmiento|Sarmiento]] running through its center east-west, with the east side [[List of car-free places|pedestrianized]] (peatonal). Other major streets, running perpendicular to Sarmiento, include Bartolom\u00e9 Mitre, San Mart\u00edn, and 9 de Julio ([[Argentine Declaration of Independence|July 9th]]), those running parallel include [[Christopher Columbus|Col\u00f3n]], and Las Heras. Four smaller plazas, San Mart\u00edn, Chile, Italia, and Espa\u00f1a, are located 2 blocks off each corner of Independence Plaza. Unique to Mendoza are the exposed stone ditches, essentially small canals, which run alongside many of the roads supplying water to the thousands of trees.[[File:Fountain of the Continents, Mendoza 02.jpg|left|thumb|Fountain of the Continents]]\n\nThe Parque General San Mart\u00edn ([[General San Mart\u00edn Park]]) was designed by [[Carlos Thays]]. Its grounds include the [[Mendoza Zoological Park]] and a football stadium, and it is also the home of the [[Universidad Nacional de Cuyo]]. A view of the city is available from the top of [[Cerro de la Gloria]] (Mt. Glory).<ref>{{cite episode | title = Barrio la gloria by Estudio Rodante | url = https://archive.org/details/ER_Barriolagloria_Mendoza_Argentina | network = Radio Comunitaria | series = El Viento | minutes = 3:02 | transcript-url =  | access-date = 2019-01-22 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070306223456/http://www.archive.org/details/ER_Barriolagloria_Mendoza_Argentina | archivedate = 2007-03-06 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n\nMendoza is {{convert|1037|km|0|abbr=on}} from [[Buenos Aires]] (13 hours by bus) and {{convert|380|km|0|abbr=on}} from [[Santiago, Chile]] (6\u20137 hours by bus). [[Governor Francisco Gabrielli International Airport|Gov. Francisco Gabrielli International Airport]] serves Mendoza, with flights to/from Buenos Aires taking less than 2 hours and less than 1 hour to/from Santiago.\n[[File:Mendoza 47 ex-Vancouver Flyer trolleybus in 2014.jpg|thumb|268x268px|Flyer E902 trolleybus]]\nThe public transport system includes buses, the [[Trolleybuses in Mendoza|Mendoza trolleybus system]], and taxis.  The trolleybuses are more comfortable than the diesel buses, but are slower, not as numerous nor is the system as extensive. In 2008, [[TransLink (Vancouver)|TransLink]] of [[Vancouver|Vancouver, British Columbia]], Canada, sold most of its old trolleybus fleet to Mendoza.<ref>[http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=a92d7053-75b0-4a20-975c-74e0ceeabfbe Aged trolleys sold to Argentine city] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105033041/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=a92d7053-75b0-4a20-975c-74e0ceeabfbe |date=2012-11-05 }}</ref>\n\nA [[heritage railway]], El Tren del Vino (The Wine Train) is being planned which will also provide local transportation; it will run through wine-producing districts of Mendoza.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.caminosdelvino.com/en/index.php?id_menu=48 |title=Mendoza Wine Train |access-date=2008-06-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625133143/http://www.caminosdelvino.com/en/index.php?id_menu=48 |archive-date=2009-06-25 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Metrotranv\u00eda===\n{{Main|Metrotranv\u00eda Mendoza}}\nA new {{convert|12.6|km|mi|adj=on}} [[light rail]] line, the [[Metrotranv\u00eda Mendoza]], opened for regular service in October 2012.<ref name=t&ut-dec2012>\"Mendoza light rail service begins\" (December 2012). ''[[Tramways & Urban Transit]]'', p. 451. [[Light Rail Transit Association|LRTA Publishing]]. {{issn|1460-8324}}.</ref> and serves five areas of the [[Greater Mendoza]] conurbation.  The line runs from {{Interlanguage link multi|Estaci\u00f3n Central|lt=|es|3=Estaci\u00f3n Central Mendoza|WD=}} (at the site of the former intercity passenger train station, near the city centre) south to [[Maip\u00fa, Mendoza|Maip\u00fa]].  The bright red railcars, [[Siemens AG|Siemens]]-[[D\u00dcWAG|D\u00fcwag]] U2 models, were purchased from the [[San Diego Metropolitan Transit System|San Diego Metropolitan Transit System (MTS)]] of San Diego, California, USA in 2010. They were built in 1980.\n\n===Transandine Railway===\n{{Main|Transandine Railway}}\nMendoza's development was helped partly due to its position at the start of the Transandine Railway linking it to [[Los Andes, Chile|Santa Rosa de Los Andes]] in Chile. The only railway operable between Argentina and Chile, after many years of inactivity, it remains currently abandoned.<ref name=\"www.diariodecuyo.com.ar\">[http://www.diariodecuyo.com.ar/home/new_noticia.php?noticia_id=345712 www.diariodecuyo.com.ar El tren trasandino] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531161611/http://www.diariodecuyo.com.ar/home/new_noticia.php?noticia_id=345712 |date=2011-05-31 }}  Accessed 22 June 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.argentour.com/local-cgi/ToForo/index.cgi?msg=1571 Volvi\u00f3 el ferrocarril a Mendoza] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611035517/http://www.argentour.com/local-cgi/ToForo/index.cgi?msg=1571 |date=2011-06-11 }} {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[http://www.seconstruye.com/webnoticia/asp/interior.asp?id=17067 En julio se licitar\u00e1 tren Los Andes - Mendoza] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310140626/http://www.seconstruye.com/webnoticia/asp/interior.asp?id=17067 |date=2007-03-10 }} {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090730130717/http://geocities.com/Baja/Mountain/4163/99_01.html  Revisiting the Transandine Railway]  - accessed 22 June 2009</ref>\n\nThe Transandine Railway is a {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}} line, with sections of [[Abt rack system|Abt rack]], whilst the railways it links with are both {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}} [[broad gauge]]. A journey from Buenos Aires to Chile involved two [[break-of-gauge|breaks-of-gauge]], and therefore two changes of train, one at Mendoza, and the other at Santa Rosa de Los Andes.\n\n==Wine industry==\n[[File:Vignoble Mendoza Argentine.jpg|alt=|thumb|388x388px|Vineyard in the [[Uco Valley]]]]\nArgentina's Malbec wines originate from Mendoza's high-altitude wine regions of Lujan de Cuyo and the Uco Valley. These districts are located in the foothills of the Andes mountains between 2,800 and 5,000 feet elevation.<ref name=\"VA\">{{cite book |last= Catena |first= Laura |title= Vino Argentino, An Insiders Guide to the Wines and Wine Country of Argentina. |publisher= [[Chronicle Books]] |year= 2010 |isbn= 978-0811873307 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/vinoargentinoins0000cate }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last= Rolland |first= Michel |title = Wines of Argentina |publisher = Mirroll |year=2006 |isbn= 978-9872092634  }}</ref><ref>[http://www.flyfishingpatagonia.com/mendoza_wine_malbec_wine_mendoza_malbec Wine Tours: Argentina \u2013 Mendoza] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112120211/http://www.flyfishingpatagonia.com/mendoza_wine_malbec_wine_mendoza_malbec |date=2011-01-12 }}, \"Fly Fishing Patagonia\"</ref><ref>[http://www.winespectator.com/webfeature/show/id/42514 Wine Tip: Malbec Madness] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802013723/http://www.winespectator.com/webfeature/show/id/42514 |date=2015-08-02 }}, \"Wine Spectator\", April 12, 2010</ref> \n\nVintner Nicolas Catena Zapata is considered the pioneer of high-altitude growing and was the first, in 1994, to plant a malbec vineyard at 5,000 feet above sea level in the Mendoza region. His family is also credited with making world-class wines and giving status to the wines of Argentina.<ref>[https://archive.is/20141126180056/http://www.argusleader.com/story/wineblog/2014/03/24/malbec-wines-have-rich-history-and-flavor/6841337/ Malbec wines have rich history and flavor], \"Argus leader\"</ref>\n\nThe subject of elevation is of much interest to the wine world because with increased altitude, the intensity of the sunlight increases. The role of this increased light intensity is currently being investigated by Catena Zapata\u2019s research and development department headed up by Laura Catena, Alejandro Vigil and Fernando Buscema.\n\n==In film==\n[[File:Mendoza - Ruta Nacional 149 en Uspallata.JPG|alt=|thumb|Scenes from [[Seven Years in Tibet (1997 film)|Seven Years in Tibet]] were filmed in [[Uspallata]].]]''[[Seven Years in Tibet (1997 film)|Seven Years in Tibet]]'', directed by French director [[Jean-Jacques Annaud]], was shot in and around Mendoza.  Several dozens of sets were built, ranging from a {{convert|220|yd|m|adj=on}} long recreation of the [[Tibet]]an capital city of [[Lhasa]] (built in the foothills of the Andes), to a {{convert|9000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} recreation of the Hall of Good Deeds in the [[Potala]], the ancient palace of the [[Dalai Lama]] (built in an abandoned garlic warehouse outside the city).\n\n==Climate==\n\nMendoza's climate is characterized as an [[arid climate|arid]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''BWh'' or ''BWk'' depending on the [[Isotherm (contour line)|isotherm]] used);<ref>{{cite journal|author=M. Kottek|author2=J. Grieser|author3=C. Beck|author4=B. Rudolf|author5=F. Rubel|title=World Map of the K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification updated|journal=Meteorol. Z.|volume=15|pages=259\u2013263|url=http://koeppen-geiger.vu-wien.ac.at/pics/kottek_et_al_2006.gif|doi=10.1127/0941-2948/2006/0130|accessdate=April 22, 2009|year=2006|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/62twqml5g?url=http://koeppen-geiger.vu-wien.ac.at/pics/kottek_et_al_2006.gif|archive-date=November 2, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> with [[continent]]al characteristics.<ref name=clima>{{cite web |url= http://www.ciudaddemendoza.gov.ar/la-ciudad/clima#titulo |language= Spanish |title= Clima |publisher= Municipalidad de la Ciudad de Mendoza |accessdate= October 6, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151005223018/https://ciudaddemendoza.gov.ar/la-ciudad/clima#titulo |archive-date= October 5, 2015 |url-status= live }}</ref> Most precipitation in Mendoza falls in the summer months (November\u2013March).<ref name=clima/> Summers are hot and humid where mean temperatures can exceed {{convert|25|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}.<ref name=clima/> Average temperatures for January (summer) are {{convert|32|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} during daytime, and {{convert|18.4|\u00b0C|1|abbr=on}} at night.<ref name=NOAA/> Winters are cold and dry with mean temperatures below {{convert|8|\u00b0C|1|abbr=on}}.<ref name=clima/> Night time temperatures can occasionally fall below freezing during the winter.<ref name=clima/> Because winters are dry with little precipitation, snowfall is uncommon, occurring once per year.<ref name=clima/> July (winter) the average temperatures are {{convert|14.7|\u00b0C|1|abbr=on}} and {{convert|2.4|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}}, day and night respectively.<ref name=NOAA/> Mendoza's annual rainfall is only {{convert|223.2|mm|1|abbr=on}}, so extensive farming is made possible by irrigation from major rivers. The highest temperature recorded was {{convert|44.4|\u00b0C|1|abbr=on}} on January 30, 2003 while the lowest temperature recorded was {{convert|-7.8|\u00b0C|1|abbr=on}} on July 10, 1976.<ref name = ORA>{{cite web |url = http://www.ora.gov.ar/eval_decadial.php |title = Mendoza (Aero), Mendoza |work = Estad\u00edsticas meteorol\u00f3gicas decadiales |publisher = Oficina de Riesgo Agropecuario |language = Spanish |accessdate = June 11, 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150630065619/http://www.ora.gov.ar/eval_decadial.php |archive-date = June 30, 2015 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = [[Mendoza Airport]], Argentina (1981\u20132010, extremes 1949\u2013present)\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 44.4\n|Feb record high C = 40.6\n|Mar record high C = 37.8\n|Apr record high C = 34.0\n|May record high C = 33.0\n|Jun record high C = 30.4\n|Jul record high C = 33.0\n|Aug record high C = 34.4\n|Sep record high C = 36.0\n|Oct record high C = 40.1\n|Nov record high C = 40.8\n|Dec record high C = 43.5\n|year record high C = 44.4\n|Jan high C = 32.3\n|Feb high C = 30.9\n|Mar high C = 27.9\n|Apr high C = 23.2\n|May high C = 18.7\n|Jun high C = 15.7\n|Jul high C = 15.0\n|Aug high C = 18.3\n|Sep high C = 21.1\n|Oct high C = 25.9\n|Nov high C = 29.2\n|Dec high C = 31.8\n|year high C = 24.2\n|Jan mean C = 25.5\n|